Discovered Item: Current leases, for platforms in both OCS and state waters, require complete removal
Federal laws and regulations now enable alternative uses after decommissioning
Agency roles in decommissioning well-defined

Competing concerns about the potential impacts of removing platforms versus leaving them in place (e.g., Potential for residual pollution from platform structure, Risk of eventual contaminant leaching from shell mounds left in place, Disturbance and dispersal of contaminants from dredging to remove shell mounds, Loss of biological communities and production with complete removal, Much larger amounts of air emissions with complete removal, both on-site and at processing and disposal sites onshore)
Alternative uses, with the exception of artificial reefing, would require eventual removal of the platform
Uncertainty about the ecological effects of artificial reefing, especially regarding the contribution of biological production on the reef to communities at the regional scale
Little concern about overall technical feasibility of complete removal, although deeper platforms may require adaptation of current methods
Technical feasibility/value of some alternative uses (e.g., wind and wave energy, aquaculture) not fully established
Feasibility of partial removal and reefing fully established
Only x platform in state waters is in water deep enough to meet requirements of the partial removal option
Liability is clearly defined and managed for complete removal
Partial removal and transfer to state ownership as artificial reef raises concerns about liability that must be addressed with new legislation and/or management policies
Liability for other alternative uses a lesser concern
Large cost of complete removal, particularly for larger platforms, a concern for operators
Alternative uses would result in cost savings
Partial removal and reefing, with a state (CA) to be allocated a share of avoided costs (i.e., savings)
